- **`mainViewTable` 목록(PC) 줄바꿈:** `default.css`의 **`body { word-break: break-all }`** 이 표 **`th`/`td`까지 상속**되면 PC에서 **작성일·`첨부파일` 헤더** 등이 글자/숫자 단위로 두 줄로 갈라진다. **`community.css`의 `.mainViewTable`** 에서 **`table-layout: fixed`**, **`th`는 `word-break: keep-all`**, **`td`는 `word-break: normal`**, 작성일·첨부·조회·번호·처리상태 열에는 **`white-space: nowrap`**(및 필요 시 **`min-width`**)로 **gunsan 목록과 같이 한 줄**을 유지한다. 제목 열은 **`.cellTitle a`만 `word-break: break-all`**(말줄임·긴 문자열)을 유지한다.
- **포털·원본 HTML 색(`--primary`):** `source/gunsan/css/default.css`와 같이 기본 포인트 색은 **`#0B8E41`**. `src/styles/userWeb/default.css`의 **`:root { --primary; --primary-light }`** 를 따르고, **`header.css`에서 `:root`로 테마색을 전역 `!important` 덮어쓰지 않는다.** `LayoutWrapper`의 **`headerType="portal"`** 인 페이지는 로그인 계정의 `data-theme`을 루트에 적용하지 않아 포털·공지·커뮤니티 본문이 학생(빨강) 테마로 바뀌지 않게 한다. 로그인 메인 등은 **`data-theme="student"|…`** 로 `header.css` 테마색이 적용된다.
- **스티키 푸터(`LayoutWrapper`):** `LayoutWrapper` 최상위는 **`class="userWebLayoutShell"`** + `src/styles/userWeb/common.css`에서 **`display: flex; flex-direction: column; min-height: 100vh`**(및 **`100dvh`**) + **`#main_content { flex: 1 0 auto }`** 로 짧은 본문에서도 푸터가 뷰포트 하단에 붙고, `body` 배경 흰색이 푸터 아래에 드러나지 않게 한다(학원 메인 등).
- **로그인 메인 교육 목록 유형 필터 (`layoutMainHtml`):** `source/gunsan/main.html`과 같이 `eduListWrap` 상단에 **`flex-sb` + `optionWrap` + `optBtnWrap`** 으로 **전체·지원사업·교육사업·홍보** 토글 버튼을 둔다. 마크업은 **`role="group"`**, **`aria-labelledby="filter-title"`**, 숨김 라벨 **`#filter-title`**(`.blind`/`.sr-only`), 각 버튼 **`type="button"`** + **`aria-pressed`**(gunsan 스크립트와 동일: 전체는 단독 선택, 나머지는 다중 토글·전부 해제 시 전체로 복귀). 스타일은 **`src/styles/userWeb/main.css`** 의 **`.eduListWrap .optBtnWrap`**(테마는 `var(--primary)` / `var(--primary-light)`). **클라이언트 필터**는 `mapApiItemToCard`의 **`categoryClass`**(`biz` | `education` | `promo`)와 맞춘다. **서버 목록 필터**가 필요해지면 동일 유형 키로 API 요청 파라미터를 붙이면 된다.

**MUST NOT:**

- Invent new class names or replace original ones with Tailwind-only equivalents when the original CSS exists.
- Drop or rename semantic/accessibility IDs (`#skip`, `#main_content`, etc.).

**Example (correct):**

```tsx
// Layout: preserve #skip and #main_content from original HTML
<>
  <div id="skip">
    <a href="#main_content">본문 바로가기</a>
  </div>
  <Header />
  <main id="main_content">{children}</main>
  <Footer />
</>

// Section: preserve original class names and structure
<section className="eduListWrap">
  <div className="inner">
    <div className="tit">지금 신청가능한 교육 목록</div>
    <div className="cardSection" aria-labelledby="sectionTitle">
      <div className="cardGrid">...</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
```

**Example (wrong):**

```tsx
// ❌ Replacing original structure with Tailwind-only
<main className="max-w-[1400px] mx-auto py-10">  // Original had id="main_content" and specific classes
<section className="flex flex-col gap-4">        // Original had className="eduListWrap"
```

### 1.3 Preserve accessibility

**MUST:**

- Keep **skip link**: a link that targets `#main_content` (or the main content ID), e.g. inside a `div` with `id="skip"`.
- Keep **ARIA and semantics** from the original: `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, `aria-hidden` where present (e.g. `aria-label="메뉴 열기"`, `aria-labelledby="sectionTitle"`).
- Keep **screen-reader-only text** (e.g. `.blind` or `.sr-only`) for labels like "기간:", "장소:" so the meaning is announced.

**Example (correct):**

```tsx
<li className="infoDate">
  <span className="blind sr-only">기간:</span> {date}
</li>
<button type="button" className="menuOpen" aria-label="메뉴 열기">
```

### 1.4 Conversion checklist

Before considering a conversion done, verify:

- [ ] Original HTML (and CSS) file(s) are in the project and referenced.
- [ ] Class names and IDs in React match the original HTML.
- [ ] Original CSS is imported and applied (no full rewrite with Tailwind for the same UI).
- [ ] Skip link and `main` ID are present; ARIA and `.blind`/`.sr-only` are preserved where they were in the source.
- [ ] Section structure (e.g. `eduListWrap`, `cardSection`, `boardSection`) is preserved in components.

### 1.5 Interactive components: vanilla scripts → React (behavior parity)

**When this applies:** The original (e.g. gunsan) uses **vanilla HTML + script** (e.g. `new Swiper('.mainSwiper', {...})` in a `<script>` block). The user web is **React** (e.g. `swiper/react`). You cannot paste the original script as-is.

**MUST:**

- **Re-implement the intended behavior** in the React way. Preserve the same **user-visible behavior** (e.g. tab order: first slide link → second slide link → prev/play/next; when focus lands on a slide link, the carousel **shows that slide**).
- Keep **original class names and DOM shape** where possible (e.g. `mainSwiper`, `visualItem`, `linkItem`). Use React components and refs for the library instance and event handlers.
- If the React library behaves differently (e.g. inactive slides get `aria-hidden` or `tabindex="-1"` and are skipped by Tab), **add equivalent behavior** (e.g. keep slides in tab order; on focus of a slide link, call `slideTo` / `slideToLoop` so the active slide changes to match focus).

**MUST NOT:**

- **Copy-paste the original `<script>` block** or assume that the same `new Swiper(...)` options alone will yield the same behavior in React; lifecycle and DOM binding differ.
- **Drop intended behavior** (e.g. "Tab moves to next slide and that slide is shown") because the original script does not explicitly show a `focus` → `slideTo` call; the original may rely on vanilla or DOM order. In React, implement that UX explicitly when the library does not.

**Check before finishing:**

- [ ] Tab order and focus behavior match the original (e.g. slide links in order, then controls).
- [ ] Focusing a slide link results in that slide being shown (slideTo/slideToLoop or equivalent).
- [ ] Class names and structure stay aligned with the original HTML for CSS and accessibility.

### 1.6 Preserve element types when reimplementing behavior (buttons vs links)

**When this applies:** The gunsan HTML uses a specific element (e.g. `<button>`, `<a>`) for an action. You need to reimplement the _behavior_ in React (e.g. navigation, form submit). The rule is: **preserve the original element type**; reimplement only the behavior.

**Root cause of a past failure (do not repeat):**

- **What happened:** On the qna page, the original gunsan `qna.html` had `<button type="button" class="btnPr">문의하기</button>`. The intended behavior was “navigate to the write page.” The implementation **replaced** the button with `<a>` / Next.js `<Link>` because “navigation ⇒ use a link” seemed semantically correct.
- **Why it was wrong:** The project rule is **preserve gunsan markup first**. The original CSS (e.g. `.bizInput .btnPr`) was written for a `<button>`. Buttons and anchors have different default layout (e.g. `display`, how content is aligned). Replacing `<button>` with `<a>` changed how `.btnPr` applied (e.g. text alignment, padding), so the UI no longer matched the original even though the same class was used.
- **Correct approach:** Keep `<button>` in React. Implement navigation with `onClick` and the router (e.g. `router.push(href)`). The DOM element and classes stay identical to gunsan; only the _behavior_ is reimplemented in the React way.

**MUST:**

- **Preserve the exact HTML element type** from the gunsan source for each interactive control: if the original has `<button>`, use `<button>` in JSX; if it has `<a href="...">`, use `<a>` or `<Link>`.
- When the original uses **`<button>`** and the intended behavior is **navigation** (e.g. go to another page), keep `<button>` and trigger navigation in React (e.g. `onClick={() => router.push(href)}` or `onClick={() => window.location.href = href}`). Do **not** replace the button with `<a>` or `<Link>`.
- When the original uses **`<a href="...">`**, use `<Link href="...">` (or `<a href="...">`) in React and preserve the same `href`/navigation target.

**MUST NOT:**

- **Do not** replace a `<button>` with an `<a>` or `<Link>` solely because the action is “go to another URL.” Preserving design parity requires preserving the element type; the existing CSS targets that element.
- **Do not** assume “semantic HTML” (e.g. “navigation ⇒ anchor”) overrides the project rule. Here, **gunsan is the source of truth**: same element + same classes = same look and behavior.

**Example (correct):**

```tsx
// Original (gunsan): <button type="button" class="btnPr">문의하기</button>
// React: keep <button>, implement navigation in onClick
const writeHref = themeQuery
  ? `/userWeb/qna/write?${themeQuery}`
  : '/userWeb/qna/write';
<button type="button" className="btnPr" onClick={() => router.push(writeHref)}>
  문의하기
</button>;
```

**Example (wrong):**

```tsx
// ❌ Replacing <button> with Link changes element type; .btnPr styling (e.g. text alignment) may not match original
<Link href={writeHref} className="btnPr">
  문의하기
</Link>
```

**Check before finishing:**

- [ ] For every interactive control, the JSX element type matches the gunsan HTML (`<button>` vs `<a>` vs `<input>` etc.).
- [ ] Navigation or other behavior is implemented via event handlers (e.g. `onClick` + `router.push`) when the original uses a button, not by swapping to a link.

